MONDAY TO THURSDAY
ISSUED BY THE MET OFFICE ON BEHALF OF THE COASTGUARD AND
MARITIME AGENCY AT 052300 UTC
MONDAY EVENING AN AZORES HIGH EXTENSION LIES OVER THE
UK. EITHER SIDE A WEAK LOW CENTRED 1001 DENMARK AND A
DEEPER LOW 974 CENTRED DUE W OF ICELAND. THE DENMARK LOW
FILLS OVERNIGHT AND THE ICELAND LOW MOVS E REACHING
ICELAND MAINLAND 978 BY MIDDAY TUESDAY. THE RIDGE OF HIGH
PRESSURE GETS PUSHED ACROSS THE CONTINENT BY A TROUGH
EXTENDING OUT OF THE ICELAND LOW. THIS TROUGH MOVS EWARDS
INTO CULLERCOATS DURING TUESDAY NIGHT WITH A RIDGE OF
HIGH PRESSURE RETURNING W OF THE UK. THE PARENT LOW
REMAINS ANCHORED ACROSS ICELAND AND SHOULD START TO FILL.
BY MIDDAY WEDNESDAY THE RIDGE MOVS E ACROSS THE UK WITH
THE TROUGH STILL LYING ACROSS CULLERCOATS AND PERHAPS
DPN. BY THURSDAY THE TROUGH IS EXP TO MOV E AND THE RIDGE
SHOULD DECLINE ALLOWING FURTHER DEEP ATLANTIC LOWS IN FM
THE W. SOME GALES LIKELY ACROSS BAILEY AND ROCKALL
